{"type":"message","id":"d770fd60","parentId":"188006ba","timestamp":"2026-05-10T10:37:25.663Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[Sun 2026-05-10 05:37 CDT] Act as a Linux Systems Architect. Perform a deep-dive diagnostic on the `asher-Legion-Slim-5-16APH8` node via the OpenClaw gateway. Execute and analyze the following to verify routing conflicts and display lockout:\n\n1. **Routing Verification:** Run `ip route show table all`. Identify if `enp2s0` is missing a gateway in the main table vs. a sub-table. Check for 'dead' routes that might be causing the stuttering.\n2. **Display Blocker Diagnostic:** Inspect the kernel ring buffer using `dmesg | grep -iE 'drm|nvidia|nouveau|backlight|i915|amdgpu'`. Look specifically for 'atomic update failure' or 'GPU fallen off the bus' errors that occurred during the last network restart.\n3. **Service Conflict Check:** Check the status of the display manager and any network-wait blockers: `systemctl status gdm` and `systemctl list-jobs`. Verify if `NetworkManager-wait-online` is currently holding a 'start' job that is blocking the GUI from initializing.\n4. **Interrupt Audit:** Run `cat /proc/interrupts | grep -E 'wlo1|enp2s0'`. Determine if the Wi-Fi card is generating excessive interrupts that are starving the GPU driver's access to the PCIe bus.\n\nOutput a concise 'Ground Truth' report. Do not suggest fixes yet; only map the current state of the hardware/network contention."}],"timestamp":1778409445658}}
