{"type":"message","id":"22c15c32","parentId":"5bbc46f9","timestamp":"2026-05-10T10:43:59.253Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"We need to run commands with sudo but cannot due to terminal requirement. We can try to run without sudo for systemctl status? Already did earlier: it shows inactive (dead). For systemctl list-jobs also we can run without sudo? Probably works. Let's try.\n\nAlso we can check for NetworkManager-wait-online status via systemctl without sudo? Likely works.\n\nWe'll run non-sudo versions for service checks.\n\nAlso we can try to read dmesg via /var/log/dmesg or journalctl? Maybe journalctl doesn't require sudo? Let's test.\n\nWe need to produce Ground Truth report. We have routing info already. Need to verify if enp2s0 missing gateway: we saw only link-local route, no gateway.\n\nDisplay blocker: we have Xorg log showing no modes requested, using NULL, virtual screen 640x480, and NVIDIA GPU reports no enabled display devices found; starting anyway because AllowEmptyInitialConfiguration is enabled. Also AMD GPU has outputs but maybe eDP-1-0 is internal display? It shows EDID found and preferred mode, so internal display likely working? But NVIDIA not driving display? However the system might be using hybrid graphics; the AMD GPU is driving the internal display (eDP-1-0). The NVIDIA GPU is disconnected (all DPF-0..3 disconnected). So display may be working via AMD GPU.\n\nBut we need to check for atomic update failure or GPU fallen off bus. Since we cannot run dmesg, we can check journalctl -k maybe? Let's try.\n\nAlso interrupt audit: we can run cat /proc/interrupts without sudo.\n\nLet's do that.\n\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"chatcmpl-tool-a6ff0a472f5cba38","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"systemctl list-jobs"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"nvidia","model":"nvidia/nemotron-3-super-120b-a12b","usage":{"input":35219,"output":384,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWri