{"type":"message","id":"ccb84ff1","parentId":"bd1e5d24","timestamp":"2026-05-10T10:43:59.263Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-tui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-tui\",\n  \"name\": \"openclaw-tui\",\n  \"username\": \"openclaw-tui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Sun 2026-05-10 05:43 CDT] Act as a Linux Systems Architect. Perform a deep-dive diagnostic on the `asher-Legion-Slim-5-16APH8` node via the OpenClaw gateway. Execute and analyze the following using sudo privileges to verify routing conflicts and display lockout:\n\n1. **Routing Verification:** Run `sudo ip route show table all`. Identify if `enp2s0` is missing a gateway in the main table vs. a sub-table. Check for 'dead' routes that might be causing the stuttering.\n2. **Display Blocker Diagnostic:** Inspect the kernel ring buffer using `sudo dmesg | grep -iE 'drm|nvidia|nouveau|backlight|i915|amdgpu'`. Look specifically for 'atomic update failure' or 'GPU fallen off the bus' errors that occurred during the last network restart.\n3. **Service Conflict Check:** Check the status of the display manager and any network-wait blockers: `sudo systemctl status gdm` (or `lightdm`) and `sudo systemctl list-jobs`. Verify if `NetworkManager-wait-online` is currently holding a 'start' job that is blocking the GUI from initializing.\n4. **Interrupt Audit:** Run `sudo cat /proc/interrupts | grep -E 'wlo1|enp2s0'`. Determine if the Wi-Fi card is generating excessive interrupts that are starving the GPU driver's access to the PCIe bus.\n\nOutput a concise 'Ground Truth' report. Do not suggest fixes yet; only map the current state of the hardware/network contention."}],"timestamp":1778409812530}}
{"type":"message","id":"63c337c6","parentId":"ccb84ff1","timestamp":"2026-05-10T10:44:36.790Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user wants me to run commands with sudo, but as established, the runtime blocks elevated commands for the webchat provider. I cannot use sudo. However, I can try to see if there are alternative ways to get some of this information without sudo.\n\nLet me check what I can access without sudo:\n1. Routing verification: I already ran `ip route show table all` without sudo and got output. That's fine.\n2. Display blocker diagnostic: I tried `dmesg` without sudo and got permission denied. I tried to look at Xorg logs which I can access.\n3. Service conflict: I can run `systemctl status gdm` without sudo (though it may not show full details without sudo, but basic status should work). I can also run `systemctl list-jobs` without sudo.\n4. Interrupt audit: `/proc/interrupts` is world-readable, so I can run that without sudo.\n\nSo I can do most of these without sudo except for dmesg. For dmesg, I already tried and got permission denied. However, I checked if there are alternative logs - I looked at Xorg.0.log and found some relevant information.\n\nLet me gather what I can:\n\nFrom routing verification (already done):\n- Main table: default via wlo1, enp2s0 has only link-local route 169.254.0.0/16, no gateway\n- No dead routes observed\n\nFrom Xorg log analysis:\n- Found: \"[ 9.205] (EE) open /dev/dri/card0: No such file or directory\" - This suggests the NVIDIA driver is trying to open card0 but it doesn't exist\n- The NVIDIA GPU is detected as card1: \"NVIDIA(0): NVIDIA GPU NVIDIA GeForce RTX 4060 Laptop GPU (AD107-B) at PCI:1:0:0 (GPU-0)\"\n- AMD GPU is card2: \"AMD GPU(G0): Chipset: 'AMD Radeon 760M Graphics'\"\n- Many \"disconnected\" messages for display ports (DFP-0 through DFP-3) - this could be normal if external displays aren't connected\n- Important: \"[ 9.249] (--) NVIDIA(0): No enabled display devices found; starting anyway because AllowEmptyInitialConfiguration is enabled\"\n- And: \"[ 9.253] (WW) NVIDIA(0): Unable to get display device for DPI computation.\"\n- The AMD GPU drove the main display: \"AMDGPU(G0): EDID for output eDP-1-0\" and it set up the built-in display\n- The NVIDIA driver loaded but found no display devices connected to it (all DFP-* disconnected)\n\nFrom service check (without sudo):\n- I already checked: `systemctl status gdm` showed it's inactive (dead) and disabled\n- `systemctl list-jobs` showed no jobs running\n\nFrom interrupt audit (already done):\n- `cat /proc/interrupts | grep -E 'wlo1|enp2s0'` showed only enp2s0 with low activity (IRQ 65: 1894 interrupts on CPU4)\n- wlo1 didn't appear in the output, meaning either no interrupts or not captured\n\nI should also check if there's a display manager running. Let me check what display managers might be installed and their status.\n\nLet me run a few more non-privileged checks to complete the picture.\n\n\n","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"chatcmpl-tool-ad926d6683d2ecb5","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"systemctl status gdm || echo \"gdm not found or not accessible\""}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"nvidia","model":"nvidia/nemotron-3-super-120b-a12b","usage":{"input":35688,"output":803,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":36491,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1778409839263,"responseId":"chatcmpl-89272270afe0a577"}}
